[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We have some ridiculous humanoid robot demos and a lot more. So, let\'s jump right in. Thanks to HubSpot for sponsoring this video. First up, we have a really useful technique for generating videos with multiple scenes that'

[01:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'transition seamlessly. So, this is called prompt relay, and this is a training-free plug-and-play method, which you can add on top of Alibaba\'s Waon. So, here\'s an example. Let\'s say for second zero to two, you have this'

[01:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'eagle flying high through the sky, and then you want to transition seamlessly into a car driving through a cyberpunk city, and then you want the camera to zoom out from a TV screen in a living room. Well, traditionally, video'

[01:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generators like Waon or LTEX can\'t really generate such huge transitions seamlessly. But, with prompt relay, you can see that the entire video is actually super smooth. It indeed was able to switch seamlessly between the'

[01:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'different scenes that you specified in your prompt. Or, here\'s yet another example where we can get this guy to place his hand on the camera, and then switch the background from a city to a desert. Everything flows naturally'

[01:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'without the prompts bleeding into the wrong parts. Here\'s how it works in simple terms. When you give the model a sequence of prompts, each tied to specific start and end times, prompt relay routes them at the cross attention'

[02:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'layers. But it makes sure that the active prompt for that time segment gets strong influence while gently handling the transitions so the whole video stays coherent. Think of it like a relay race'

[02:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'where each prompt hands off cleanly to the next person. The awesome thing is they\'ve released this already. So if you click on this code button and you scroll down a bit, it seems like they\'ve released the implementation instructions to this, but they haven\'t released the'

[02:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'files yet. So maybe it\'ll take them a few more days. If you\'re interested in reading further, I\'ll link to this page in the description below. Next up, we have a family of really unique open source models called Ternary Bonsai. Now'

[02:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this is basically a family of ultra efficient 1.58 bit language models, which I\'ll explain in a second, that allows you to basically run AI on just consumer or edge devices. So what'

[03:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'exactly is this Ternary model? Well, in simple terms, most language models today store their parameters using 16-bit precision. These are basically the dials and knobs in the neural networks of the'

[03:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'model. Now this gives them a lot of numerical detail, but it also makes them really heavy and memory intensive. That\'s why like most large language models are like hundreds of gigabytes in size. But Ternary Bonsai flips that idea'

[03:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and instead restricts every weight in the model to just three possible values, -1, 0, or 1 with a small shared scaling factor applied on top. And this makes it way more efficient. Now here you can see'

[03:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that they\'ve released three different models in this family. One is 8 billion parameters, another is 4 billion, and finally the smallest one is 1.7 billion parameters. And what\'s interesting is how small these models are. Here it says'

[03:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it\'s nine times smaller than standard 16-bit models while outperforming most of them. So, if you look at this chart, notice that the 8-billion parameter model is only 1.7 GB in size, which is like almost 10 times smaller than Qwen 3'

[04:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '8B. But yet, its performance or intelligence is almost as good despite being like 10 times smaller. It also outperforms other similar models in its class including Mistral, Llama, Llama'

[04:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '3.1, GLM-4 across all these benchmarks. So, you\'re seeing consistent gains across reasoning, coding, and knowledge tasks while being a lot smaller and more efficient. If you look at this'

[04:30] [scene:talk]
